Design a principled approach to handling the tension between static analysis rules and legitimate exceptions in a team environment. Any real codebase will have code that violates a quality rule for a documented and defensible reason: a complex function that cannot be simplified without losing clarity, a large class that represents a true domain concept, code that is complex because the underlying problem is complex. The challenge is designing a suppression and exception system that allows legitimate exceptions without becoming a mechanism for teams to silence all warnings and defeat the purpose of the tool.

Reason through the following design dimensions. First, the inline suppression mechanism: most linters allow comments like # noqa or // NOLINT to suppress individual warnings. This is convenient but creates invisible exceptions that new developers do not understand. Should suppression comments be required to include a reason? Should they expire after a time period? Should they be counted and reported as a metric (number of suppressions per file may indicate a team that is gaming the system)? Second, the baseline file approach: some tools (mypy, tsc) allow generating a baseline of all current violations, then only reporting new violations introduced after the baseline. This enables gradual improvement without making a legacy codebase block CI on day one. What are the failure modes of this approach — can teams add to the baseline to avoid fixing things? Third, the rule configuration hierarchy: should rule thresholds be configurable globally, per directory, per file, or per function? More granularity means more flexibility but also more ways to misconfigure. What is the right configuration granularity for a production tool used by a team of 10-50 developers? Fourth, the governance problem: who in an organization should have the authority to change quality thresholds, add suppressions, or modify the baseline? How should the tool enforce that these changes are reviewed and documented rather than made silently by individual developers under time pressure?
